When the user changes the OrigSuppNum ComboBox inside the popup,
âž¡ï¸ clear/reset the OrigSupplierName ComboBox in that same popup editor.

âœ… Updated onSupplierNumChange() for Popup Edit Mode

Hereâ€™s the correct version for popup editing:

function onSupplierNumChange(e) {
    // 'e.sender' is the OrigSuppNum ComboBox
    var combo = e.sender;

    // Find the popup editor container
    var popup = combo.wrapper.closest(".k-window-content");

    // Find the OrigSupplierName ComboBox inside the same popup
    var supplierNameCombo = popup.find("[name='OrigSupplierName']").data("kendoComboBox");

    if (supplierNameCombo) {
        supplierNameCombo.value("");
        supplierNameCombo.text("");
    }

    // Optional: also update your current model if youâ€™re tracking it manually
    if (window.currentNscPartsModel) {
        currentNscPartsModel.set("OrigSupplierName", "");
    }
}

ðŸ§  Why This Works

In popup mode, the editor elements live inside a Kendo Window (.k-window-content).

combo.wrapper.closest(".k-window-content") reliably finds the correct popup (even if multiple grids are open).

Then, .find("[name='OrigSupplierName']") searches only inside that popupâ€™s form â€” avoiding interference with other open popups or grids.

âœ… Bonus: Handle â€œsame value reselectedâ€ case

If you want the event to fire even when the same supplier number is reselected,
attach your logic to both the change and select events of the OrigSuppNum ComboBox:

.Events(events =>
{
    events.Change("onSupplierNumChange");
    events.Select("onSupplierNumChange");
})


That ensures youâ€™ll always clear the supplier name when the user interacts with the number field.
